<font color="#FF0000">REPLIES TO GERALD AND DOC DEL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Mar 17 13:14:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald,<br><br>
Thanks for correcting me about 'gook'.  Maybe the movies I've seen were wrong, but to believe those, gook was a common term for the enemy.  I admit I don't know anything about the psychology of battle in the Vietnam War.  I admit I was assuming that soldiers were taught to hate the enemy.  It would be too difficult to kill them if you didn't hate them was my thinking.  But I can't fathom what it would be like to actually be in mortal combat with other humans.  'Hell' is the only thing that comes to mind to describe it.  That's why I feel really bad for Vets and feel compelled to do whatever I can, in my own small way, to work for disarmament and peace, and also to recognize and honor the sacrifices you all made for your country, regardless of the larger political dynamics of the times, which at your age back then probably were way over your head anyway.  Even today with the benefit of 20-20 hindsight, and all the writing and study that has been done on the war, reading both sides of the debate, I still have difficulty understanding what the war was all about, and which side to believe.  Maybe there is no right answer, except to do whatever we can to prevent any such thing from happening again.  A good place to start would be a moratorium on weapons sales to foreign nations.<br><br>
Doc Del,<br><br>
Thanks for your compliment about my writing.  Everytime I think 'it's time for me to butt out of this' one of you guys comes along with something like that.<br><br>
I think its really cool that we can come from different generations, different sides of the debate (I'm a committed peace activist - i.e. a 'protester') yet have productive discussions and find common ground.<br>

